{"corpusName":"rsc-journals","keywords":{"teeft":["node","centrality measure","essentiality","essential gene","coli","betweenness","centrality","degree centrality","closeness","barabasi","biosyst","royal society","betweenness centrality","functional linkage","gene essentiality","closeness centrality","individual node","partial correlation","growth condition","gene","conditional essentiality","conditional network","graph theoretical","random graph model","degree distribution","other node","biological network","shortest path","functional linkage network","pearson correlation","conditional","linkage","molecular biosystems","system biology","conditional gene essentiality","such gene","such prediction","graph theory","large network","complex system","small world network","real world network","network theory","various centrality measure","small number","complete network","scale free network","essential node","protein interaction dataset","relative importance","centrality feature","centrality parameter","strong correlation","centrality ranking","pairwise pearson correlation","up diagonal","centrality pair","lower diagonal","other hand","biological function","support vector machine","input vector","unit step","true positive","true negative","false positive","false negative"]},"author":[{"name":"P. Manimaran","affiliations":["Centre for DNA Fingerprinting and Diagnostics, Hyderabad 500001, Gruhakalpa, 5-4-399/B, Nampally, India","E-mail: shekhar@cdfd.org.in"]},{"name":"Shubhada R. Hegde","affiliations":["Centre for DNA Fingerprinting and Diagnostics, Hyderabad 500001, Gruhakalpa, 5-4-399/B, Nampally, India","E-mail: shekhar@cdfd.org.in"]},{"name":"Shekhar C. Mande","affiliations":["Centre for DNA Fingerprinting and Diagnostics, Hyderabad 500001, Gruhakalpa, 5-4-399/B, Nampally, India","E-mail: shekhar@cdfd.org.in"]}],"arkIstex":"ark:/67375/QHD-M0H2WSHN-W","language":["eng"],"originalGenre":["article"],"abstract":"The genome of an organism characterizes the complete set of genes that it is capable of encoding. However, not all of the genes are transcribed and translated under any defined condition. The robustness that an organism exhibits to environmental perturbations is partly conferred by the genes that are constitutively expressed under all the conditions, and partly by a subset of genes that are induced under the defined conditions. The conditional importance of genes in conferring robustness can be understood in the context of the functional attributes of these genes and their correlations to the defined environmental conditions. However, a priori prediction of such genes for a given condition is yet not possible. We have attempted such predictions by integrating the available gene expression data with genome-wide functional linkages through the well known centralitylethality correlations in graph theory. We make use of three distinct concepts of centrality, namely, degree, closeness and betweenness, which yield mutually complementary information. We then demonstrate the efficacy of combined graph theoretical and machine learning approaches in ranking essential nodes from a large network of genome-wide functional linkages, which yields predictions with high accuracy. We therefore perceive such predictions as highly useful in applications such as defining and prioritizing drug targets.","qualityIndicators":{"hasStructuredBody":true,"teiSource":"grobid","xmlStats":{"paragraphCount":29,"sectionCount":13,"sectionLevels":[{"level":0,"sectionCount":13}],"sectionDepth":1,"imageCount":3,"tableCount":2,"refCount":37},"tdmReady":true,"score":9.448,"pdfWordCount":5529,"pdfCharCount":28760,"pdfVersion":1.6,"pdfPageCount":8,"pdfPageSize":"595.276 x 779.528 pts","pdfWordsPerPage":691,"pdfText":true,"refBibsNative":true,"abstractWordCount":204,"abstractCharCount":1403,"keywordCount":0},"title":"Prediction of conditional gene essentiality through graph theoretical analysis of genome-wide functional linkages","pmid":["19763329"],"hasFormula":true,